    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-10-05T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-10-05T04:00:00-05:00" n="604"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d604">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.7762/5: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-10-05T12:00:00+03:00"
                            >October 5, 1940—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 4:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1286. The press today publishes a communiqué reporting the signature on October 4
                    in Berlin of an agreement for passenger and freight rail communication between
                    the Soviet Union and Germany. The communiqué states that the negotiations were
                    carried out in a favorable atmosphere by the People’s Commissar for Ways of
                    Communication of the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics and by the Chief of the
                    Administration of the German Railways.</p>
                <p>Although the communiqué gives no details in regard to the proposed direct rail
                    connection I am informed by a member of the German Embassy that the agreement
                    will provide for two direct lines between <pb facs="0579" n="567"
                        xml:id="pg_567"/> Moscow and Berlin: one, Moscow–Negoreloe–Warsaw–Berlin and
                    the other, Moscow-Dvinsk–Tilsit–Koenigsberg–Berlin. Service on these roads it is
                    stated will begin within the next few days.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Berlin.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
